Cao <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utibishatter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TibisHatter</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/9/01 6:47:15 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.top-hat.demon.co.uk/Images/tibhd40.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Zen and the Art of Evade Mechanics</span><hr size=1> My opinion on the reasons for the upcoming changes to evade?  (As if you guys need another opinion)<br>
<br>
At present, if a mob requires 60 people to kill it, you'll see quite a few (5, 6 or more) rogues.  This, in Verant's eyes, kills class diversity on the top level raids.  After all, (this example for illustration purposes only) why have a ranger when a rogue does twice the damage and doesn't get killed for it?<br>
<br>
It therefore followed that the game designers concerned about this decided that some mechanism needed to be introduced which would have the end result of effectively limiting the number of rogues present on such encounters.  Significantly reducing the effectiveness of Evade has obviously presented itself as this limiting mechanism.  With the arguments put forth, the three-rogue death sequence looks like a real possibility, making me think that Evade has been tuned to this point so raid leaders have the choice of either only including two rogues, or limiting the use of additional rogues which means that in the end you may as well have only brought two along and grabbed some additional warriors and clerics instead (after all, with the extra time it's going to take to drop the boss mobs you'll need the extra tanks and healing) because it'll be as, or more, effective to do that than have more rogues.<br>
<br>
In conclusion: rogues are considered to be too additive in a multi-group raid setting.  Six rogues were nigh-on six times as good as one rogue.  Modifying evade is the mechanism chosen to forcing diminishing returns on the efficiency of rogues added to a raid.<br>
<br>
The result: There probably will be fewer rogues on raids as it becomes inefficient to use them.  This sounds like it's in line with Verants desire to make epic battles more challenging and to increase class diversity on multi-group raids. <p><HR align="CENTER" width="50%"><BR><img  src="http://www.top-hat.demon.co.uk/Images/tibissig42.jpg" usemap="#tibissignew8f631b" border="0" alt="Tibis Heartseeker"><map name="tibissignew8f631b"><area href="http://www.fdsoftware.com/eq" coords="142,154,298,174" shape="rect" alt="The Reapers of Fate"><area href="http://www.wolverineinternet.com/ring/wardens.php3?orderby=server" coords="142,134,298,154" shape="rect" alt="The Safehouse Ring"></map></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukarlek.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Karlek</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/9/01 8:24:35 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.main-rheiner.de/homepage/julius.makanec/karl/skarsaur12.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Zen and the Art of Evade Mechanics</span><hr size=1> NO EVADING:<br>
